White Wine Quality Analysis by Mehdi Jafari

This data set contains 4898 white wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine,
providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Univariate Plots Section

Our dataset consists of eleven variables with 4898 observations. Here is the
list of all the variables.

Quality

We can see in the following diagram that the quality has a fairly normal distribution.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.000   5.000   6.000   5.878   6.000   9.000

Fixed Acidity

The distribution of fixed acidity is normal, 50 percent of the observations have between 6.300 to 7.300 g/dm^3 tartaric acid.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.800   6.300   6.800   6.855   7.300  14.200

Volatile Acidity

The amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste. This variable seems to have many outliers as the mean is 0.2782 and the maximum value in the distribution is 1.1.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0800  0.2100  0.2600  0.2782  0.3200  1.1000

Citric Acid

Citric Acid is found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines. 75 percent of observations have less than 0.3900 g/dm^3 citric.acid while the max is 1.66 mg.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.0000  0.2700  0.3200  0.3342  0.3900  1.6600

Residual Sugar

The amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet. Based on the definition, none of the wines in our dataset is considered as sweet wine. The distribution of residual sugar is right skewed. We will look into this variable later on.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.600   1.700   5.200   6.391   9.900  65.800

Chlorides

Chlorides is the amount of salt in the wine. As its depicted in the following plot, it has right skewed distribution.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## 0.00900 0.03600 0.04300 0.04577 0.05000 0.34600

Free Sulfur Dioxide

The free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    2.00   23.00   34.00   35.31   46.00  289.00

Total Sulfur Dioxide

We can see in the following diagram that the quality has a normal distribution and there are only three significant outliers.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     9.0   108.0   134.0   138.4   167.0   440.0

Density

The density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content. This variable has only 3 outliers in our dataset.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.9871  0.9917  0.9937  0.9940  0.9961  1.0390

PH

Describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   2.720   3.090   3.180   3.188   3.280   3.820

Sulphates

A wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, which acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.2200  0.4100  0.4700  0.4898  0.5500  1.0800

Alcohol

The percent alcohol content of the wine. There is no outlier in alcohol distribution.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    8.00    9.50   10.40   10.51   11.40   14.20

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The given dataset contains 11 variables (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol and quality). All the variables are numerical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature in our dataset is quality. In this report will try to find a correlation between other variables and quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your into your feature(s) of interest?

residual sugar, volatile acidity, density and alcohol could have correlation with quality of wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

In order to have a better diagram, quality is categorized into four factors (bad (0-4), average (4-6), good (7-8) and excellent (9-10))

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the formthe data? If so, why did you do this?

As it is mentioned earlier residual.sugar and chlorides have right skewed distribution then a log10 transformation is applied to these variables. the plots are depicted in the following:

As it is shown in the above mentioned result, the following pairs have the most correlation with each other:

  • density and residual.sugar
  • total.sulfur.dioxide and free.sulfur.dioxide
  • density and total.sulfur.dioxide

since free.sulfur.dioxide is a subset of total.sulfur.dioxide, we will not investigate those pairs.

Since the alcohol has the greatest correlation with quality which is the main factor, plot the correlation of these two variable could be helpful.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Multivariate Plots Section

Multivariate Analysis

Relationships observed in investigation

As it was represented in the plots we can see the good white wins have less than 20mg of residual.sugar and less than 7.5 volatile acidity. Also, Good wines tend to have more alcohol and less density.

Interesting or surprising interactions between features?

As it was mentioned earlier, the combination of alcohol, density and alcohol affects the quality of wine.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This diagram depicts the correlation between quality and alcohol. Excellent wines seem to have between 11 and 14 percent alcohol.

Plot Two

Description Two

High quality wines have less than 20mg residual.suger. As it is presented in the diagram the less residual.suger and the more alcohol the more chance you have a better quality wine.

Plot Three

Description Three

High quality wines have less than 8g volatile acidity. As it is presented in the diagram the less residual.sugar and the less volatile acidity the more chance you have a better quality wine.

Reflection

In this project, I analyzed the effect of different variables of white wine on its quality based on the dataset that contained 4,898 observations with 11 variables on the chemical properties. I categorized the quality of wine into 4 groups (bad, average, good, excellent). I found out that good wines tend to have more alcohol and less sugar.

I cant expand my findings to the other white wine datasets since my sample is not a random dataset from all type of white wines, its a sample of wines of a specific region in Portuguese called Vinho Verde. And, there might be a combination of several variables (more than two) would outcome to a perfect that wasnt investigated in this project.
